</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umosushi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mosushi</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 219<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/6/02 3:57:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2252.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> There is no soft-cap</span><hr size=1> What there is a diminishing return on AC.  There ARE two types of AC.  As most beta-folks remember, AC used to have two displayed components (mitigation and avoidance), just like ATK had two (to-hit and to-dam).  People were confused and the numbers were combined into a composite.  Yep, VI has stated that there are still two parts, just not displayed as such.<br>
<br>
Whether a MOB can hit you or not depends on his level, your level, the MOB's ATK, and your avoidance AC.  For very high level or strong MOB's, the ATK value is so high that 1000 AC is essentially the same as 1500 AC.<br>
<br>
How much a MOB hits you for depends on his level, your level, the MOB's ATK, and your mitigation AC.  Just like for whether or not he hits, for very high level or strong MOBs (65, Statue of RZ, etc.), their ATK is so high that there's just not much difference between 1000 and 1500.  Statue hits for 1100'ish at 1200 ac and for 1100'ish at 1500.  Basically, that extra 500 AC doesn't help.<br>
<br>
The area where more AC doesn't matter is very easy to see when xp'ing.  After an AC upgrade or hefty AC buff, you'll notice that a particular MOB that used to hit for a variety of values will typically only hit for it's minimum value.  Most folks seem to feel that the limit on useful AC is somewhere between 1100 and 1300.  Everyone pretty much agrees that beyond this, you'll want to get +100 hp items in every slot.  BTW, yes, even casters can break 1000 AC with a nice end-game set.  A lot of the end-game items are all/all.  Usually, only enchanters care about AC/HP, though.  It's pretty amazing to see the beating some high-end enchanters can take and live. <p>Mosushi, Lizard Master of the Fish<br>
<i>"I will gladly pay you Tuesday for Sushi today!"</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubloodandsin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bloodandsin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 176<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/6/02 6:49:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2252.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: AC soft cap and such?</span><hr size=1> I come from the school of thought that 1250 is the number to reach as a warrior, then after that go all on out into HP.  <br>
